  "prompt": "What does \"ride or die\" mean and where did it come from?",
  "response": "\"Ride or die\" is a popular slang phrase that refers to someone who is extremely loyal and willing to support and stick with another person no matter the circumstances, even in the face of danger or adversity. The phrase suggests that the person would be willing to \"ride\" with someone through the good times and the bad, and even \"die\" for them if necessary.\n\nThe origins of the phrase are not entirely clear, but it is believed to have emerged from African American Vernacular English (AAVE) in the United States during the late 20th century. The phrase gained wider popularity in the 1990s and 2000s, particularly in the context of hip-hop culture and music.\n\nOne of the earliest recorded uses of the phrase is in the 1997 song \"Ruff Ryders' Anthem\" by DMX, which includes the lyrics, \"Stop, drop, shut 'em down, open up shop, oh, no, that's how Ruff Ryders roll, n***as wanna try, n***as wanna lie, then n***as wonder why, n***as wanna die, all I know is pain, all I feel is rain, how can I maintain, with that s***t on my brain, I resort to violence, my n***as move in silence, like you don't know, n***a, we be ridin', ridin', ridin', yo, yo.\"\n\nSince then, the phrase has been widely used in popular culture, including in movies, television shows, and music. It is often used to describe a close friend, romantic partner, or family member who is seen as a loyal and dependable companion.",
